  "text": "HTT and MAOA blockade during early postnatal development increase adult anxiety/depression-like behavior Early postnatal 5-HTT blockade increases anxiety/depression-like behavior in adult mice. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] Because 5-HTT and MAOA blockade both increase 5-HT signaling, we hypothesized that early postnatal MAOA blockade would also increase adult anxiety/depression-like behavior. To test this hypothesis, we administered the 5-HTT blocker fluoxetine (FLX, 10 mg kg − 1 per day, i.p.), the MAOA inhibitor clorgyline (CLO, 20 mg kg − 1 per day, i.p.), or vehicle (VEH, 0.9% NaCl, i.p.) to mice in the early postnatal (PN) period, from postnatal day 2-21 (P2-P21) and assessed emotional behavior in adulthood (P90). To investigate developmental specificity, we also tested mice that received FLX, CLO and VEH in the peri-adolescent period (ADO), from postnatal day 22-41 (P22-P41). To control for the effects of the injection procedure, we included naïve littermates in our behavioral tests.",
